00:00:08,130 --> 00:00:12,100
So I've given you two different types of
statistics for talking about

2
00:00:12,100 --> 00:00:15,980
the relationship between a risk factor, or
a treatment, and a disease.

3
00:00:15,980 --> 00:00:19,080
Absolute risk differences, and relative
risk differences.

4
00:00:19,080 --> 00:00:21,350
So which of those gives a more clear and

5
00:00:21,350 --> 00:00:25,288
honest picture of the association between
treatment and exposure or disease?

6
00:00:25,288 --> 00:00:30,010
Turns out that, authors love relative
risks.

7
00:00:30,010 --> 00:00:31,210
They're easy to interpret.

8
00:00:31,210 --> 00:00:33,320
You don't have to worry about units.

9
00:00:33,320 --> 00:00:36,730
They, that's what predominates in the
medical literature.

10
00:00:36,730 --> 00:00:41,690
Unfortunately, relative risks are actually
less informative than absolute risks,

11
00:00:41,690 --> 00:00:45,220
and it's often useful to see the absolute
risks in addition to,

12
00:00:45,220 --> 00:00:48,050
or instead of, the relative risks.

13
00:00:48,050 --> 00:00:50,030
Relative risks can mask some things.

14
00:00:50,030 --> 00:00:54,580
For example, you can have a dramatic
increase or decrease in relative risk that

15
00:00:54,580 --> 00:00:59,250
corresponds to a very, very tiny increase
or decrease in absolute risk.

16
00:00:59,250 --> 00:01:04,710
So for example, if the risk in one group
is 0.001% and

17
00:01:04,710 --> 00:01:08,910
the risk in an exposed group is 0.003%.

18
00:01:08,910 --> 00:01:11,430
If you compare those two groups in terms
of a relative risk,

19
00:01:11,430 --> 00:01:12,960
it comes out to be a relative risk of 3.

20
00:01:12,960 --> 00:01:15,480
That sounds large and dramatic.

21
00:01:15,480 --> 00:01:19,790
But if you simply subtract the absolute
risks and you focus on the absolute risks

22
00:01:19,790 --> 00:01:23,535
you can see that the actual increase in
risk is extremely small.

23
00:01:23,535 --> 00:01:28,320
0.002% is a really small increase in risk
for a, for an individual.

24
00:01:28,320 --> 00:01:31,090
So you can see that the picture looks very
different.

25
00:01:31,090 --> 00:01:34,615
Often the relative look, risks look more
dramatic and

26
00:01:34,615 --> 00:01:38,442
impressive but the asset risks are most
honest.

27
00:01:38,442 --> 00:01:42,149
So, let's just give you an example here.

28
00:01:44,320 --> 00:01:47,930
The Women's at Health Initiative was a
large randomized double blind

29
00:01:47,930 --> 00:01:52,280
study looking at the effect of
postmenopausal hormones versus placebo on

30
00:01:52,280 --> 00:01:54,600
a number of outcomes in postmenopausal
women.

31
00:01:54,600 --> 00:01:58,650
And this study was run in the late 1990s
and the early 2000s.

32
00:01:58,650 --> 00:02:02,066
And before the study was done, it was
widely believed that.

33
00:02:02,066 --> 00:02:06,420
Women, postmenopausal women, benefited
greatly from taking hormones.

34
00:02:06,420 --> 00:02:09,540
In particular it was believed to reduce
the risk of heart disease.

35
00:02:12,100 --> 00:02:17,180
Well that study was actually stopped early
in 2002 because it turned out

36
00:02:17,180 --> 00:02:22,980
that the hormones were more harmful, much
more harmful than anyone expected.

37
00:02:22,980 --> 00:02:23,680
It was.

38
00:02:23,680 --> 00:02:26,590
Expected that the hormones might increase
the risk of breast cancer.

39
00:02:26,590 --> 00:02:28,640
We kind of already knew that, of that
association.

40
00:02:28,640 --> 00:02:32,920
But the data on the heart disease actually
came out exactly the opposite of

41
00:02:32,920 --> 00:02:33,950
what people were expecting.

42
00:02:33,950 --> 00:02:37,810
It turned out that they were seeing in the
data already that the hormones were

43
00:02:37,810 --> 00:02:41,570
significantly increasing, not protecting
against heart disease but

44
00:02:41,570 --> 00:02:43,380
increasing the risk of heart disease.

45
00:02:43,380 --> 00:02:46,450
So they actually stopped the study early
as a result.

46
00:02:46,450 --> 00:02:49,670
That was pretty pretty big news, because
at the time they

47
00:02:49,670 --> 00:02:55,030
stopped that study there were 14 million
women taking post-menopausal hormones.

48
00:02:55,030 --> 00:02:59,610
So you can imagine that they must have
thought very carefully about how to

49
00:02:59,610 --> 00:03:03,130
deliver the message to not only to
physicians, but

50
00:03:03,130 --> 00:03:07,000
to the many women in the public taking
hormones at the time.

51
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:11,140
And, actually somebody did a really,
really great job in

52
00:03:11,140 --> 00:03:15,390
thinking very carefully about how to
present the risk information.

53
00:03:15,390 --> 00:03:19,760
The media coverage was extremely well
done, and this had, largely had to do

54
00:03:19,760 --> 00:03:23,050
with the fact that the press release that
was released about the study to the media.

55
00:03:23,050 --> 00:03:27,810
They, they talked about the risks in a
very particular way, and

56
00:03:27,810 --> 00:03:31,270
the media ended up just repeating what was
in the press release.

57
00:03:31,270 --> 00:03:32,900
And, and it went like this.

58
00:03:32,900 --> 00:03:36,400
They said the data indicate that if 10,000
women take the drugs for

59
00:03:36,400 --> 00:03:39,012
a year, eight more will develop invasive
breast caner,

60
00:03:39,012 --> 00:03:42,160
compared with 10,000 who were not taking
hormone replacement therapy.

61
00:03:42,160 --> 00:03:45,450
Notice they are presenting, presenting the
incidence rates,

62
00:03:45,450 --> 00:03:46,940
the difference in incidence rates.

63
00:03:46,940 --> 00:03:49,800
They're presenting everything also
everything in whole numbers, which is,

64
00:03:49,800 --> 00:03:52,020
you know, again, easier for people to
understand.

65
00:03:52,020 --> 00:03:53,850
An additional seven will have a heart
attack,

