126
00:07:25,610 --> 00:07:28,670
And thousand, several thousand breast
cancer cases per year.

127
00:07:28,670 --> 00:07:31,390
So the risk to any individual woman is
small here, but

128
00:07:31,390 --> 00:07:34,890
the risk to society is large.

129
00:07:34,890 --> 00:07:37,420
So, just think about all of these things
when you're presenting risk and

130
00:07:37,420 --> 00:07:39,370
talking about risk.

131
00:07:39,370 --> 00:07:42,150
First of all, most people have an easier
time understanding whole numbers than

132
00:07:42,150 --> 00:07:43,510
percentages and decimals.

133
00:07:43,510 --> 00:07:46,840
So it's great to always try to translate
things into whole numbers.

134
00:07:46,840 --> 00:07:49,880
Absolute risks give a more accurate
picture of the true risk than

135
00:07:49,880 --> 00:07:50,600
relative risks.

136
00:07:50,600 --> 00:07:53,620
Relative risks can look really dramatic
even when the absolute risk

137
00:07:53,620 --> 00:07:55,040
increase isn't, isn't very big.

138
00:07:55,040 --> 00:07:58,710
And then the other take home message from
this study is that,

139
00:07:58,710 --> 00:08:02,340
interestingly, you know, the public health
risk can be large even when the risk to

140
00:08:02,340 --> 00:08:03,580
a given individual is small.

141
00:08:03,580 --> 00:08:07,820
So sometimes, depending on whether you're
looking from the societal perspective or

142
00:08:07,820 --> 00:08:10,820
the individual perspective, those risks
may, you know,

143
00:08:10,820 --> 00:08:12,270
